title: Grateful Dead Live at Soldiers' and Sailors' Memorial Hall on 1979-12-11
description: Jack Straw, Loser, Me & My Uncle-> Big River, Althea, Easy To Love You, Minglewood Blues, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider Shakedown Street-> Samson & Delilah, Ship of Fools, Terrapin Station-> Lost Sailor-> Saint Of Circumstance-> Drums-> Not Fade Away-> Black Peter-> Sugar Magnolia, E:Alabama Getaway-> E: Promised Land

reviews.review_text: Saint Yes! Just for the pause (complete stop) between Lost Sailor and the EXTREMELY juicy sweet beginning of St. of Circumstance - It is a must! I love this era of The Grateful Dead. Thick, mellow, alive and jazzy. A great audience recording energy-wise and quuality.

Sailor > Saint.  Ahhh, The Pause That Refreshes. Yes Dan, that complete stop between Sailor > Saint and the sweet Saint beginning is one of the coolest moments I have ever heard from The Guyz.  It is definitely a five star attraction.  I played it over and over and over the other night because it was sooo unusual.  And isn't that what we all live for?

The position of this FOB recording is good.  And the sound is also good for the majority of the show.  

But god I love that pause!...and the > Jam > Drumz > NFA post.  So I'm going to fib on my star selection, just to draw folks in to read these reviews so they won't pass by this Sailor > Saint.  I've been instructed to say three Hail Marys and four Our Fathers with that little white lie...(w/ folded hands) let us pray for forgiveness - because the rest of this lackluster show (including the bodies of both Sailor > Saint) isn't even worth three stars as the other reviewers lament.
Sailor>Saint pause is cool But the rest of the show is just undistinguished in a year chock full of sleepers. The Black Peter gets a nod for a SMOKING rendition.
I'll second capndoubledose Kinda disappointing. Along with the night before, the boys seem to be losing steam in 79, which is an excellent year.
